Anthropic_Output: {"scientific_contributions_summary": "Marie Curie was a pioneering research scientist best known for her discovery of the element radium. She was the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and the first person to win a second Nobel, ranking alongside Albert Einstein in scientific influence during the 20th century. After moving to Paris to attend the Sorbonne, she excelled in physics and mathematics, and began her groundbreaking research on radioactivity. In 1898, she announced the possibility of a new radioactive element, and together with her husband Pierre Curie, she discovered two new elements: polonium and radium. The Curies spent years isolating these elements from pitchblende ore, culminating in Marie isolating a decigram of pure radium by 1902 and determining its atomic weight. Their work led to the birth of the Atomic Age. Marie Curie was awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1903 (shared with Pierre Curie and Henri Becquerel) for their work on radioactivity, and in 1911 she received a second Nobel Prize, this time in Chemistry, for isolating metallic radium. She also developed the medical use of X-ray technology, especially during World War I, where she equipped and operated mobile radiological units to treat wounded soldiers. {"file_name": "CONTRIBUTING.md", "repository": "microsoft/vscode", "text_content": "Contributing to VS Code

Welcome, and thank you for your interest in contributing to VS Code!

There are several ways in which you can contribute, beyond writing code. The goal of this document is to provide a high-level overview of how you can get involved.

Asking Questions

Have a question? Instead of opening an issue, please ask on Stack Overflow using the tag visual-studio-code.

The active community will be eager to assist you. Your well-worded question will serve as a resource to others searching for help.

Providing Feedback

Your comments and feedback are welcome, and the development team is available via a handful of different channels.

See the Feedback Channels wiki page for details on how to share your thoughts.

Reporting Issues

Have you identified a reproducible problem in VS Code? Do you have a feature request? We want to hear about it! Here's how you can report your issue as effectively as possible.

Identify Where to Report

The VS Code project is distributed across multiple repositories. Try to file the issue against the correct repository. Check the list of Related Projects if you aren't sure which repo is correct.

Can you recreate the issue even after disabling all extensions? If you find the issue is caused by an extension you have installed, please file an issue on the extension's repo directly.

Look For an Existing Issue

Before you create a new issue, please do a search in open issues to see if the issue or feature request has already been filed.

Be sure to scan through the most popular feature requests.

If you find your issue already exists, make relevant comments and add your reaction. Use a reaction in place of a "+1" comment:

👍 - upvote
👎 - downvote

If you cannot find an existing issue that describes your bug or feature, create a new issue using the guidelines below.

Writing Good Bug Reports and Feature Requests

File a single issue per problem and feature request. Do not enumerate multiple bugs or feature requests in the same issue.

Do not add your issue as a comment to an existing issue unless it's for the identical input. Many issues look similar but have different causes.

The more information you can provide, the more likely someone will be successful at reproducing the issue and finding a fix.

The built-in tool for reporting an issue, which you can access by using Report Issue in VS Code's Help menu, can help streamline this process by automatically providing the version of VS Code, all your installed extensions, and your system info. Additionally, the tool will search among existing issues to see if a similar issue already exists.

Please include the following with each issue:

- Version of VS Code
- Your operating system
- List of extensions that you have installed
- Reproducible steps (1... 2... 3...) that cause the issue
- What you expected to see, versus what you actually saw
- Images, animations, or a link to a video showing the issue occurring
- A code snippet that demonstrates the issue or a link to a code repository the developers can easily pull down to recreate the issue locally
  - Note: Because the developers need to copy and paste the code snippet, including a code snippet as a media file (i.e. .gif) is not sufficient.
- Errors from the Dev Tools Console (open from the menu: Help > Toggle Developer Tools)

Creating Pull Requests

- Please refer to the article on creating pull requests and contributing to this project.

Final Checklist

Please remember to do the following:

- Search the issue repository to ensure your report is a new issue
- Recreate the issue after disabling all extensions
- Simplify your code around the issue to better isolate the problem

Don't feel bad if the developers can't reproduce the issue right away. They will simply ask for more information!

Follow Your Issue

Once submitted, your report will go into the issue tracking workflow. Be sure to understand what will happen next, so you know what to expect and how to continue to assist throughout the process.

Automated Issue Management

We use GitHub Actions to help us manage issues. These Actions and their descriptions can be viewed here. Some examples of what these Actions do are:

- Automatically close any issue marked info-needed if there has been no response in the past 7 days.
- Automatically lock issues 45 days after they are closed.
- Automatically implement the VS Code feature request pipeline.

If you believe the bot got something wrong, please open a new issue and let us know.

Contributing Fixes

If you are interested in writing code to fix issues, please see How to Contribute in the wiki.

Thank You

Your contributions to open source, large or small, make great projects like this possible. Thank you for taking the time to contribute."}

Short version: You may close your Account at any time. If you do, we'll treat your information responsibly.

1. Account Cancellation

It is your responsibility to properly cancel your Account with GitHub. You can cancel your Account at any time by going into your Settings in the global navigation bar at the top of the screen. The Account screen provides a simple, no questions asked cancellation link. We are not able to cancel Accounts in response to an email or phone request.

2. Upon Cancellation

We will retain and use your information as necessary to comply with our legal obligations, resolve disputes, and enforce our agreements, but barring legal requirements, we will delete your full profile and the Content of your repositories within 90 days of cancellation or termination (though some information may remain in encrypted backups). This information cannot be recovered once your Account is canceled.

We will not delete Content that you have contributed to other Users' repositories or that other Users have forked.

Upon request, we will make a reasonable effort to provide an Account owner with a copy of your lawful, non-infringing Account contents after Account cancellation, termination, or downgrade. You must make this request within 90 days of cancellation, termination, or downgrade.

3. GitHub May Terminate

GitHub has the right to suspend or terminate your access to all or any part of the Website at any time, with or without cause, with or without notice, effective immediately. GitHub reserves the right to refuse service to anyone for any reason at any time.

4. Survival

All provisions of this Agreement which, by their nature, should survive termination will survive termination — including, without limitation: ownership provisions, warranty disclaimers, indemnity, and limitations of liability."}

{"average_rating": 4.26, "top_3_user_reviews": ["2024: Each time I read what PBS dubs the perfect American novel, my heart fills just a little more. There are few books where the beginning paragraphs hit a home run for me, and this is one of them. It has been a long month filled with family time and endless cooking so for the last ten days I opted for comfort reads and there is no family who provides comfort like the Finches, with the exception of Aunt Alexandra. “Lawyers were children once,” quotes Charles Lamb in the opening epithet. Prior to this reading, I viewed Atticus Finch as an unapproachable, older father. Beloved by his children to the point of idolization, but with an impenetrable outer skin. As an adult looking back at the events which shaped the novel, Scout paints the picture of her father as one who makes everything right and makes her feel safe. Even though this novel had been marketed for adults, it is in its essence a coming of age novel, which shows Scout’s growth through elementary school while her family faces events that mean to alter the history of a town. Atticus would need to be a strong figure to guide his children through the plot, and he would need to wistfully remember his childhood in order to relate to them. This is the man who told us all to walk in another’s shoes and see things from their point of view. Until today, I never viewed Atticus as multi-faceted, just a great man. Today that view slightly changed, yet he remains one of my top personas of all time.

Pestering Boo Radley is like killing a mockingbird, Scout implores Atticus. He never did anyone harm. There is a reason why this novel won the Pulitzer as being ahead of its time. The beginning and ending paragraphs mirror each other and provide closure. Scout and Dill engage in childhood escapades while learning life lessons imparted on them by their neighbors. Jem believes that the story began the summer Dill came and he tried to make Boo Radley come out. Being four years Scout’s senior at the time, he already saw the events of the novel from an adult perspective. Scout and Dill did not. They started as innocent seven year olds who thought that they would get married one day and ended as empathetic individuals who wanted to change the world. Perhaps Atticus’ lessons had penetrated these children after all; Scout, at least, looked like a lawyer in the making. If the world changed in her lifetime, perhaps she would get that opportunity.

With a book as perfect as this one, it comes as little wonder to me that Harper Lee never published another in her lifetime. She became a recluse; perhaps she modeled Boo Radley after her own tendencies. Boo did not come out because he did not want to. I am of the camp who is 99.9% sure to never read Go Set a Watchman. To Kill a Mockingbird is practically perfect in every way and made to change the way a nation thought about groups of people. Harper Lee had as much courage in publishing it pre- Civil Rights Act as the characters in her novel did in living with there preconceived notions of how the world functions. Bravery, courage, and empathy remain the overarching motifs in this great American novel. I view it as the ultimate comfort read and in the words of my reading friend Tessa, five stars and a heart.", "/// gentle reminder that this is not the time to read this book ///

This is my first re-read of 2017, and I don't regret it one bit. When I first read this book three years ago, I really liked it. Sadly, I didn't write my thoughts down in an elaborate way back in the day, but I know for sure, that I didn't read critically then. Upon my re-read of this book, I honestly don't have good things to say. I am aware that some of my criticism is not a critique of the book itself, but about its perception, and how it is, up to this day, held up as the one true book about race relations in the United States of America.

And that really infiruates me. This book was written by a white woman, from a white perspective, about white characters, for a white audience. This book is a pat on the back for the white middle class. Comfort that they, especially back in the 1960s, didn't need, and allow me to be so bold, didn't deserve.

Harper Lee's focus is purely white. While the white characters in this book are the subjects, who take action into their own hands, who suffer and make sacrifices, the Black characters in this book are objects. They have little to no agency. Things happen to them. They are harmless, defenseless, and just there – waiting for the white knight hero, Atticus Finch, to save them. This book is a disgrace in the face of the Black liberation movements that existed back in the day, and the solidarity within Black communities. Black people stood up for themselves and fought for their rights, and only due to their voices, their protests, their sit-ins, their marches, their demonstrations, their conferences, was racial segregation made unconstitutional in the United States.

Black people, back then and now, know that Atticus Finch doesn't exist. And because no one put in better words than the one and only James Baldwin, I will quote a passage from one of his amazing interviews on the Dick Cavett Show in 1968. One could say that this is Baldwin's response to the cry of "not all white people":
James Baldwin: I don't know what most white people in this country feel. But I can only conclude what they feel from the state of their institutions. I don't know if white Christians hate Negroes or not, but I know we have a Christian church which is white and a Christian church which is black. That says a great deal for me about a Christian nation. [...] I don't know whether the labor unions and their bosses really hate me - that doesn't matter - but I know I'm not [allowed] in their union. I don't know whether the real estate lobby has anything against black people, but I know the real estate lobby is keeping me in the ghetto. I don't know if the board of education hates black people, but I know the textbooks they give my children to read and the schools we have to go to. Now, this is the evidence. You want me to make an act of faith, risking myself, my wife, my woman, my sister, my children on some idealism which you assure me exists in America, which I have never seen.
This right here is what I'm talking about. To Kill A Mockingbird plays into this idealism. Although the book touches on the horrors of racism in the Deep South, it’s a strangely comforting read. A terrible injustice is done, but at the end the status quo is reassuringly restored. The final message is that most (white) people are nice when you get to know them.

As a reader you are never allowed to feel with Tom Robinson, the Black man who is innocently convicted for raping a white woman, because all the Black characters in this tale are sidelined. This story should be about them, because how else would you be able to convince the white moderate (in the 1960s) that Black people are actually people. The closest insight we get to a Black character is the family's cook Calpurnia. Calpurnia is in the fictional tradition of the "happy black", the contented slave – the descendent of the ever-loyal Mammy in Gone With the Wind. And the rest of the Black community is depicted as a group of simple, respectful folk – passive and helpless and all touchingly grateful to Atticus Finch – the white saviour. We never see any of them angry or upset. We never see the effect of Tom Robinson’s death on his family up close – we don't witness Helen, Tom's wife, grieving and Scout never wonders about his children. Their distress is kept at safe distance from the reader.

I was very angry after finishing this book, and I'm still angry up to this day. Not necessarily at Harper Lee, but at our society as a whole, and at our educational system. Why do we constantly uplift white narratives, whilst brushing over marginalized ones? Why aren't our kids reading If Beale Street Could Talk by James Baldwin – a book dealing with the exact same topic (a Black man getting falsely accused of raping a woman)? Why isn't Lorraine Hansberry required reading? Why are we still relying on white narratives, when talking about Black people and their struggles?

Since finishing this book, I started reading The History of Legal Education in the United States and I wanted to share some interesting facts, because I couldn't believe how absurd To Kill A Mockingbird was. This story is, supposedly, set in the Deep South in the 1930s, where Atticus Finch, our white saviour, takes it upon himself to defend a Black man at court. By the end of Lee's novel we are led to believe that Atticus had a great chance of actually getting Tom Robinson acquitted, if the latter had just been a "good n*gger" and didn't try to escape on his own. (Yes, I'm a little petty. I swear, I'm not turning bitter over this.) So, I just wanted to know how realistic that scenario is. All of the information is related to the 1930s Southern setting. Here's what I've learned:

Most Southern lawyers readily accepted Black clients for routine economic cases – property, tort, contract, dept, insurance – and minor criminal cases that did not threaten the South's system of racial hierarchy. It was virtually impossible, however, to find a Southern white lawyer who would accept a major criminal case involving a white victim or a politically charged case that in any way challenged segregation.

Only the combination of direct action, community organizing and legal strategy with the help of Black lawyers, made the defense of Black men and women at court possible. In the Lockett-case, the Black community in Tulsa survived largely because Black lawyers were able to defend the community's interests. In 1934, Black lawyers represented George Crawford, a Black man accused of brutally murdering a wealthy white woman – no white lawyer would take Crawford's case. In the end, Crawford got a sentence of life imprisonment instead of a death sentence. And this verdict had to be seen as an accomplishment by the Black lawyers and the Black community as a whole, because life imprisonment was as good as it was going to get.

Oftentimes, Black lawyers took serious criminal cases without a fee or at a very reduced rate. This was well appreciated by their communities, but also a given. It is admirable how well Black communities were organized. None of that got translated on the pages of Lee's novel. The Black characters do absolutely nothing, except sending Atticus food, because they're so grateful. [*insert snort here*]

This book appears to uphold the standard of racial equality; de facto it is about the white middle class patting themselves on the back for not thinking racist thoughts. I'm sorry to break it to you, Miss Maudie, but you won't get a sugar cookie for that. I am not saying that this is not a realistic portrayal of the white middle class, it is, it totally is. If you do just a little research on the Civil Rights movement, the moral apathy of the white middle class becomes crystal clear. However, we shouldn't portray these characters in a positive light, there is nothing admirable about them. After all...
He who passively accepts evil is as much involved in it as he who helps to perpetrate it. He who accepts evil without protesting against is really cooperating with it.

- Martin Luther King, Jr.", "6.0 stars. I know I am risking a serious “FILM AT 11” moment and a club upside the head from Captain Obvious for voicing this, but nabbit dog I still think it needs to be said…TO KILL A MOCKINGBIRD is one of the BEST and MOST IMPORTANT American novels ever written. Okay, I said it, and I will wait patiently while you get your DUHs and DERs out of the way and hang your “no shit” signs outside for Inspector Holmes.

Okay, now given the gruntload of reviews/ratings this book has I know I’m not the first person to wag my chin about how amazing it is. Still, I am going to chance coming off like that annoying dingleberry at the tail end of a huge porcelain party because I truly have a pile of love for this book. …(Sorry for taking the metanalogy there just now, but I promise no more poop references for the rest of the review)... So if my review can bring a few more people into the Atticus Finch Fan Club, I will be just flush with happy.

On one level, this book is a fairly straight-forward coming of age story about life in a small Alabama town during the Great Depression. It has a very slice of lifesaver warmth and simplicity to it that I think resonates with a lot of readers. It certainly does with me and I think the adjective “charm” may have been invented to describe the novel.

Despite how easing flowing the narrative is, this book is both extremely and deceptively powerful in its discussion of race, tolerance and human decency. Most importantly, this book shows us by example the courage to stand all up in the grill of injustice and say “Not today, Asshole! Not on my watch.”

That is a lesson that I think we can never be reminded of too often. When bad people do bad things to good people, the rest of us good people need to sack up and be counted regardless of how scary it might be. Easier said then done, I know. But at least that should be the standard to which we strive.

Atticus Fitch is the epitome of that standard. He is the role model to end all role models and what is most impressive is that he comes across as such a REAL person. There is no John Wayne/Jack Bauer/Dirty Harry cavalry charging BSD machismo about him. Just a direct, unflinching, unrelenting willingness to always do what he thinks is right. As Atticus’ daughter Scout puts it so well:

Anthropic_Output:
{"video_title": "Resident Evil Village Review", "video_description": "Resident Evil fête ses 25 ans, et au lieu d'un gros gâteau plein de viscères de zombies, on a droit au huitième épisode de la saga, premier sur une nouvelle génération de consoles. Resident Evil Village continue de suivre l'histoire d'Ethan Winters. Le mari modèle parti sauver sa femme dans le bayou passe papa de l'année à la recherche de son bébé tombé dans les griffes des villageois les plus flippants d'Europe centrale. Après l'excellent Resident Evil 7 on attendait cet épisode de pied ferme, et on est loin d'être déçus.

Resident Evil n’a jamais autant eu le vent en poupe. Et pourtant, la série a fait du chemin depuis ses débuts il y a 25 ans. Et quels 25 ans! Quelle autre série peut se vanter de s’inventer et se réinventer pas une, pas deux, mais trois fois? Alors que Resident Evil revitalise le survival horror en caméra fixe en 1996, un genre inventé par Alone in the Dark en son temps, Resident Evil 4 exécute un revirement action à la troisième personne brillant en 2005. Puis Resident Evil 7 fait en 2017 le pari, réussi, de passer la série à la première personne. On oublie quelques malheureux faux pas (je te vois, RE6), et on passe par quelques remakes qui s’offrent le luxe d’être une référence de ce qu’un remake de jeu vidéo doit accomplir, pour arriver à ce tout dernier Resident Evil Village. Une belle aventure qui génère forcément des attentes, mais on est vite rassurés manette en main: on a bien là un nouveau grand chapitre de cette épopée.

Resident Evil Village (attention, un 8 en chiffres romains se cache dans ce titre, le coquin) prend la suite directe des événements de Resident Evil 7. On reste dans la peau d’Ethan Winters, le nouveau protagoniste de RE7 dont on ne montrera jamais le visage. L’horreur de ce qui lui est arrivé dans le bayou de la Louisiane est bien loin derrière lui et il est parti se la couler douce en Europe avec Mia, sa femme sauvée héroïquement des griffes moisies de la famille Baker, et leur fille Rose qui vient de naître. Et il vécurent heureux, jusqu’à ce que Chris Redfield et son commando armé débarque un soir sans même téléphoner avant, pour abattre cette pauvre Mia à la mitraillette et embarquer le bébé Rose. Mais pourquoi est-il aussi méchant? C’est ce qu’Ethan va s’efforcer de découvrir.

Village People

Sur la piste de sa fille, Ethan arrive finalement dans le fameux village du titre. L’endroit est pittoresque, surplombé par son château, mais Ethan n’aura pas le temps de faire du tourisme. Il est immédiatement évident que les rues sont truffées de lycans qui ne manqueront pas une opportunité pour tenter de le croquer. Les vils résidents du village apportent une bonne variété d’adversaires. Pas de zombies au programme ici, on est loin des laboratoires d’Umbrella, mais plutôt une large panoplie d’horreurs inspirées du folklore Européen, avec ses loup-garous, ses vampires, et autres créatures variées qui ont le mérite d’apporter une diversité bienvenue dans les challenges proposés.

Le jeu ne dira jamais où se déroule exactement son action, mais l’inspiration bohémienne est évidente et le château semble tout droit sorti des mythes de Transylvanie. L’histoire du jeu vous fera rencontrer des figures locales hautes en couleurs à mesure que vous explorerez leurs domaines, et découvrirez les mystères de la région, et leur lien avec la mythologie Resident Evil au sens large. Aucun élément de l’histoire n’est laissé au hasard, et chaque pièce du grand puzzle a sa place. Que ce soit Ethan et sa famille, les Baker, l’étrange moisissure qu’il a découvert en Louisiane, l’implication de Chris Redfield, tout a un lien, et bien sûr, Umbrella.

Le village comme ses occupants sont d’une beauté à couper le souffle. Ici, le RE Engine fait clairement des miracles. L’ambiance glauque, les reflets sur les marbres du château, les effets de lumière et le poil soyeux des loup-garous sont au service d’une atmosphère angoissante maîtrisée à la perfection. Sur la Playstation 5 qui a servi de plateforme de test, la lumière du soleil filtrée dans le brouillard flippant à force de HDR ou la réflexion ray-tracée des torches sur la pierre laissent sans voix, et le tout à 60 images par secondes ou presque, s’il vous plaît. Un véritable tour de force et vitrine technologique pour cette nouvelle génération de consoles. On regrette cependant une irrégularité sur la qualité des textures, puisque le jeu peut parfois à l’inverse sombrer dans le baveux décevant notamment dans les espaces les plus ouverts.

Toujours sur Playstation 5, la Dualsense est utilisée timidement. On apprécie de sentir le poids des armes plus ou moins lourdes dans la gâchette adaptative, mais l’utilisation des fonctionnalités de la manette s’arrête là.

Le U est muet

La star des premières heures de Resident Evil Village est, comme son nom ne l’indique pas, son château. La gigantesque et opulente résidence de la non moins gigantesque et opulente Dame Dimitrescu est là pour donner au fan de Resident Evil ce qu’il attend: une immense demeure à explorer, avec ses couloirs labyrinthiques, ses portes fermées à clé, ses énigmes tordues et ses secrets. Tout ça sous l'œil terrifiant de Dame Dimitrescu, une vampire de 2m90 accompagnée de ses trois filles aussi charmantes qu’affamées. La petite famille vampirique fera aussi office de Nemesis. Le principe de l’ennemi invincible et persistant est emblématique dans Resident Evil. Que ce soit un M. X dans Resident Evil 2, le Nemesis de Resident Evil 3 ou Papa Baker dans Resident Evil 7, la menace perpétuelle d’un grand méchant ultra puissant et omniprésent est toujours là. Avec cette fois un peu plus de charme et de crocs que d’habitude, mais ne vous y méprenez pas, entendre les talons de ces dames sur le sol en marbre du château vous glacera immédiatement le sang.

Et si le château Dimitrescu rappelle autant Resident Evil 7 dans son gameplay, c’est pour mieux prendre le joueur à contrepied par la suite. Le château n’est pas le seul point d’intérêt du village, et Ethan aura l’occasion de rendre visite à d’autres éminents villageois dans leurs antres respectives, offrant à chaque fois un changement de ton et d’ambiance étonnant et une diversité dans le gameplay. Chaque grande section du jeu peut même être vue comme un hommage spécifique aux différentes niches du jeu d’horreur, et aux autres Resident Evil.

Cette variété est un des grands points forts du jeu qui ne sera jamais répétitif. L’aventure vous prendra une dizaine d’heures, et se vit comme un voyage dont les thèmes, les adversaires, et le gameplay, vont changer pour apporter un renouveau perpétuel jusqu’aux crédits de fin. Les puzzles parviennent à rappeler les classiques ultra kitsch d’un Resident Evil d’il y a 25 ans tout en apportant de la nouveauté, avec l’inclusion parfois d’une bonne dose de simulation physique par exemple.

L’idiot du Village
On va pas se mentir, on est parfois restés bien bêtes devant certains puzzles. Resident Evil nous a habitués à un type de puzzle très spécifique. On met le rubis dans le trou, et la porte s’ouvre. Et si y a un cheval dessiné sur la porte, c’est que la clé cheval est pas loin. Mais ici, Resident Evil Village prend par surprise. Il faudra parfois se servir de la physique pour faire balancer des lanternes pendues à des chaînes, ou propager du feu. Vos armes explosives pourront par endroit faire écrouler un mur, ou dégager des renforts en bois. Et n’oubliez pas de lire attentivement les documents que vous trouvez : ils sont rarement placés au hasard et comportent souvent des indices critiques sur les puzzles et les ennemis du coin.

Les boss sont extrêmement nombreux et variés, et vous donneront l’occasion d’exploiter votre arsenal à la recherche de leurs points faibles. Certains seront des combats à distance favorisant l’utilisation d’armes telles que le fusil sniper, alors que d’autres testeront votre adresse au combat rapproché, fusil ou lance grenades à la main. Les boss, tout comme les ennemis normaux les plus balaises, mettront à l’épreuve votre sens de la stratégie. Évidemment, il est toujours possible de vider quelques chargeurs complets de fusil à pompe dans leur gueule, mais c’est pas forcément la solution la plus économe. Il sera toujours plus intéressant de détecter un point faible, une partie du corps plus exposée, un détail de l’environnement pouvant servir de piège, ou même l’endroit idéal pour placer une mine bien fourbe. Creusez-vous les méninges, et vous serez souvent récompensé.

Les Mercenaires sont de retour
Grand classique de la série, le mode Mercenaires fait son grand retour dans Resident Evil Village. L’aspect angoissant du jeu passe à la trappe, et est remplacé par un bon vieux massacre bourrin de loup garous et autres horreurs dans les environnements de la campagne. Ici, l’objectif est la survie, et surtout le score. Enchaînez les combos, surveillez le chrono, et soyez le plus efficace possible pour faire exploser les compteurs, et récolter les récompenses. Pas de risque de vous spoiler le jeu: le mode Mercenaires se débloque après avoir terminé l’histoire.

Buffé contre les vampires

Resident Evil Village n’a pas peur d’introduire des nouveaux systèmes, et d’en emprunter d’autres à de précédents jeux de la série, qu’on n’avait pas vu depuis longtemps. Au cœur de ces systèmes, le Duc, un marchand mystérieux qui arpente les rues du village pour vous proposer ses marchandises contre de l’argent. Un principe qui n’est pas sans rappeler celui de Resident Evil 4.

L’argent, vous en trouverez partout : vos ennemis en laisseront derrière eux à leur mort, soit en cash, soit en trophées qu’il sera possible de revendre au Duc. Voir les différents adversaires larguer du butin donne un côté un peu arcade à Resident Evil Village, mais permet de récompenser les risques et l’investissement de munitions.

Le Duc pourra même vous préparer des petits plats, histoire de vous apporter quelques buffs pour votre aventure. Malheureusement la mise en œuvre de l’idée est un peu maladroite, les effets proposés ont peu d’impact sur le gameplay, et on se retrouve finalement à massacrer le bétail du village pour récupérer sa viande plutôt gratuitement.

On emprunte toujours à Resident Evil 4 son système d’inventaire qui est là de manière symbolique. On fait un peu de Tetris pour ranger ses balles mais rien de bien plus complexe que ça, vous aurez largement la place de tout porter et n’aurez pas à courir d’un coffre à l’autre pour gérer votre inventaire. Des coffres, il n’y en a pas d’ailleurs, vous aurez toujours votre arsenal avec vous. Les munitions sont éparpillées dans le village en quantité limitée, mais suffisante pour profiter de toutes les armes à votre disposition. Le jeu vous laisse même un peu de flexibilité grâce à un système de fabrication d’équipement, à travers lequel vous pourrez fabriquer des stocks de balles pour votre arme de prédilection.

Les Resident Evil ont souvent oscillé entre le pur survival horror, et le jeu davantage orienté action. Village est nettement orienté vers cette seconde catégorie. Stock de munitions (relativement) généreux, inventaire large, butin lâché sur chaque victime, checkpoints et sauvegardes automatiques sans machines à écrire, tout est là pour faciliter le parcours du joueur et le laisser se plonger dans l’ambiance, plutôt que de gérer les outils de sa survie.

Un Duc et du loot
Le Duc est le marchand local. Vous le croiserez souvent à proximité des machines à écrire, dans les zones les plus sûres du jeu. Le Duc porte de multiples casquettes: marchand, cuistot, ou encore guide spirituel. En plus de visiblement être au courant de tout ce qui se passe dans le coin, il vous aidera à refaire votre stock de munitions, améliorer vos armes, et faire un peu de cuisine en échange de quelques pièces.

On garde l’excellente carte de Resident Evil 2 Remake, qui indique clairement les salles qui n’ont pas été suffisamment fouillées. Salle rouge? Il reste du butin. Salle bleue? On peut passer à la suite. Mais dans un jeu qui comprend un grand nombre de points de non retour surprise, les perfectionnistes compulsifs (on se soigne) contempleront des salles devenues inaccessibles jusqu’à la fin de l’aventure. D’autant plus qu’il est parfois rageant, et frustrant, de fouiller de fond en comble une salle pour finalement trouver l’objet qui manquait: un petit éclat de cristal qui brillait dans un recoin, et qu’on revendra pour trois fois rien au Duc.

Mais on pinaille, bien sûr. On est bien obligés de pinailler d’ailleurs, car lorsqu’il s’agit de montrer du doigt les points négatifs du jeu, on est rapidement désarmés. Resident Evil Village présente une expérience aboutie, qui va au bout de ses promesses, qui sait prendre le joueur par surprise, et qui ose prendre des risques quasiment sans fausse note.

Verdict

Capcom a vu grand avec Resident Evil Village. Il s’agissait là de répéter le succès du passage à la première personne de la série, et de poursuivre l’aventure d’Ethan Winters. On prend un plaisir immense à suivre l’histoire d’Ethan, qui passe de p’tit nouveau au rang de personnage majeur de la série. Son périple bourré de rebondissements nous pousse à nous attacher à ce père prêt à tout pour sa fille, et arrivés aux crédits de fin, on ne peut s’empêcher d’être impatients d’avoir la suite. Mais Resident Evil Village se donne également pour objectif de proposer un voyage à travers l’histoire de la série et du jeu d’horreur en général, multipliant les surprises et les revirements d’ambiance, tout en ajoutant quelques éléments nouveaux pour enrichir encore davantage la proposition. Le résultat est bluffant à tous les niveaux, et une réussite totale. 25 ans plus tard, Resident Evil n’a pas pris une ride et n’a jamais été en meilleure forme.", "video_url": "https://fr.ign.com/resident-evil-8/53871/review/test-resident-evil-village-bienvenue-dans-le-fan-club-de-lady-dimitrescu"}

Insulin helps move glucose from your bloodstream into your cells, where it can be used for energy. If you have diabetes, your body can't make insulin, can't use insulin as well as it should, or both. - Researchers think gestational diabetes is caused by the hormonal changes of pregnancy along with genetic and lifestyle factors.", "treatments": "Treatment for diabetes involves managing your blood glucose levels:
- If you have type 1 diabetes, you will need to take daily doses of insulin, either by injection or through a special pump. Some people also need to take another type of diabetes medicine that works with insulin.

- If you have gestational diabetes, you may be able to lower your glucose levels by eating a healthy diet and getting regular exercise. But be sure to talk to your provider about your treatment options. Gestational diabetes usually goes away after you give birth. But you will have a higher risk of developing type 2 diabetes later.

# Review of Spaghetti Carbonara Recipe

★★★★★

This Pasta Carbonara recipe is an absolute gem! The simplicity of the ingredients—just pancetta (or bacon), eggs, cheese, and pasta—belies the incredible depth of flavor in the final dish. The creamy sauce that forms from the eggs and cheese is luxurious without being heavy, and the salty, crispy pancetta adds the perfect contrast of texture and flavor.

What I appreciate most about this recipe is how authentic it feels. No cream is added, which stays true to the traditional Italian preparation. The dish comes together quickly (30 minutes total!) making it perfect for a weeknight dinner that feels special enough for company.

The instructions were clear and straightforward, making what could be an intimidating dish very approachable. I particularly liked the notes about the traditional use of guanciale versus the more accessible pancetta or bacon options.

# Modified Review with Additional Details about Helpful Cooking Techniques

★★★★★

This Pasta Carbonara recipe is an absolute gem! The simplicity of the ingredients—just pancetta (or bacon), eggs, cheese, and pasta—belies the incredible depth of flavor in the final dish. The creamy sauce that forms from the eggs and cheese is luxurious without being heavy, and the salty, crispy pancetta adds the perfect contrast of texture and flavor.

The cooking techniques in this recipe were incredibly helpful, especially for someone who's new to making carbonara. **The method for tempering the eggs** was game-changing—whisking in some pasta water with the beaten eggs and working quickly after draining the pasta prevented the dreaded "scrambled egg" effect that can ruin carbonara. I found the tip about having the beaten eggs at the ready in a bowl with some cheese already mixed in to be crucial for timing.

Another technique that made a huge difference was **allowing the pasta to cool just slightly** before adding the egg mixture. This delicate balance—pasta hot enough to cook the eggs but not so hot that they curdle—is the key to that silky sauce. The visual cues in the recipe ("use tongs to move it to the bowl with the bacon and garlic" and "let it be dripping wet") helped me achieve the perfect consistency.

The recommendation to **use high-quality Parmesan** also can't be overstated. As the recipe notes, "if you're going to indulge, why not do it right?" That real, freshly grated Parmesan melts beautifully into the sauce and provides a depth of flavor that pre-packaged cheese simply can't match.

If you're looking for a restaurant-quality pasta dish that won't break the bank or take hours to prepare, this carbonara recipe is absolutely worth trying!"

# Flutter Dropdown Alignment Issue Q&A

## Question: Flutter dropdown alignment not proper

**Asked:** 5 years, 2 months ago (but still relevant and recently answered)

**Problem Description:**
The user wants to implement a dropdown menu in Flutter but is experiencing alignment issues where the dropdown menu items are overlapping the button itself. When clicking the dropdown button, the menu items appear on top of the button rather than below it.

**Code Provided:**
```dart
DropdownButtonFormField(
  isExpanded: false,
  isDense: true,
  items: classes.map((category) {
    return new DropdownMenuItem(
      value: category,
      child: Row(
        children: <Widget>[
          Text(category),
        ]
      ),
    );
  }).toList(),
  onChanged: (newValue) {
    // do other stuff
  },
  value: _classroom,
  decoration: InputDecoration(
    contentPadding: EdgeInsets.fromLTRB(10, 0, 10, 0),
    enabledBorder: UnderlineInputBorder(
      borderSide: BorderSide(color: Colors.white)),
    hintText: "Select Class",
    hintStyle: TextStyle(
      color: Colors.grey[500],
    ),
  ),
)
```

**Question Statement:** "Is this achievable with dropdown widget? If not, how can I design custom dropdown widget?"

## Answers:

### Answer 1 (highly rated):
Flutter does show the dropdown menu below the menu button by default. The reason it's overlapping in this case is because there are too many items in the menu that can't fit all on the screen, which pushes the menu up to be able to show more of them.

The answerer suggested looking at the `DropdownButtonFormField` class in the code and selecting "Go to source" to understand how the built-in dropdown works.

### Answer 2 (comprehensive solution):
Use Flutter's `DropDownButton2` package, which allows better alignment of menu items from the bottom of the button. With this package, you can easily customize the menu items.

The answer provided multiple design examples with different situations:
- Basic dropdown with items aligned below button
- Custom styling options for dropdown items
- Menu with icons and different layouts
- Form field style dropdowns

**Code Solution:**
```dart
ButtonTheme(
  alignedDropdown: true,
  child: DropdownButtonFormField(
    ...
  )
),
```

The comprehensive answer included visual examples showing proper alignment and references to the package documentation.

## Key Takeaways:
1. Flutter's default dropdown widget can have alignment issues when there are many items
2. The `alignedDropdown: true` property in ButtonTheme can help with proper alignment
3. For more complex customization, third-party packages like DropDownButton2 offer better control
4. Understanding the source code of Flutter's UI components helps solve alignment issues
5. Custom dropdown widgets can be created when built-in solutions don't meet requirements

This Q&A demonstrates how Flutter developers address UI alignment challenges in cross-platform mobile development, which continues to be a trending area in mobile app development."

"I've encountered another CAPTCHA verification screen. Since we keep hitting these verification barriers, I'll proceed with composing a comprehensive answer about Python data types based on the information I've gathered from Stack Overflow so far.

# Python Data Types: A Comprehensive Overview

Python is a dynamically typed language with several built-in data types that form the foundation of Python programming. Below is a detailed explanation of Python's core data types with well-formatted code examples.

## Numeric Types

### Integers
```python
# Integer examples
x = 10
y = -5
z = 0

# In Python 3, integers have unlimited precision
big_num = 123456789012345678901234567890
```

### Floating-Point Numbers
```python
# Float examples
a = 3.14
b = -0.001
c = 2.0
d = 1.23e-4  # Scientific notation: 1.23 × 10⁻⁴
```

### Complex Numbers
```python
# Complex number examples
complex_num1 = 3 + 4j
complex_num2 = complex(3, 4)  # Same as 3 + 4j

# Accessing real and imaginary parts
print(complex_num1.real)  # 3.0
print(complex_num1.imag)  # 4.0
```

## Sequence Types

### Lists
```python
# Lists are ordered, mutable sequences
fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
mixed_list = [1, "hello", 3.14, True]

# List operations
fruits.append("orange")        # Add item to end
fruits.insert(1, "blueberry")  # Insert at index 1
fruits.remove("banana")        # Remove by value
popped_item = fruits.pop()     # Remove and return last item
fruits.sort()                  # Sort the list in-place

# List comprehensions
squares = [x**2 for x in range(10)]  # [0, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81]
```

### Tuples
```python
# Tuples are ordered, immutable sequences
coordinates = (10, 20)
rgb = (255, 0, 128)
single_item_tuple = (42,)  # Note the comma for single-item tuples

# Tuple unpacking
x, y = coordinates  # x = 10, y = 20

# Tuples are often used for multiple return values
def get_dimensions():
    return (1920, 1080)  # returns width, height as a tuple

width, height = get_dimensions()
```

### Strings
```python
# Strings are immutable sequences of Unicode characters
greeting = "Hello, World!"
multiline = """This is a
multiline string"""

# String methods
upper_text = greeting.upper()         # "HELLO, WORLD!"
lower_text = greeting.lower()         # "hello, world!"
split_text = greeting.split(", ")     # ['Hello', 'World!']
joined_text = ", ".join(["A", "B"])   # "A, B"

# String formatting
name = "Alice"
age = 30
formatted = f"{name} is {age} years old"  # "Alice is 30 years old"
```

## Mapping Type

### Dictionaries
```python
# Dictionaries store key-value pairs
person = {
    "name": "John",
    "age": 30,
    "city": "New York"
}

# Access, modify and add items
print(person["name"])      # John
person["age"] = 31         # Update value
person["email"] = "john@example.com"  # Add new key-value pair

# Dictionary methods
keys = person.keys()       # dict_keys(['name', 'age', 'city', 'email'])
values = person.values()   # dict_values(['John', 31, 'New York', 'john@example.com'])
items = person.items()     # dict_items([('name', 'John'), ('age', 31), ...])

# Dictionary comprehension
squares_dict = {x: x**2 for x in range(5)}  # {0:0, 1:1, 2:4, 3:9, 4:16}
```

## Set Types

### Sets
```python
# Sets store unordered collections of unique elements
fruits_set = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"}
numbers = {1, 2, 3, 2, 1}  # Will contain {1, 2, 3}

# Set operations
fruits_set.add("orange")   # Add element
fruits_set.remove("banana")  # Remove element (raises KeyError if not found)
fruits_set.discard("kiwi")   # Remove if present (no error if not found)

# Set operations (mathematical)
set1 = {1, 2, 3}
set2 = {3, 4, 5}
print(set1 | set2)  # Union: {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
print(set1 & set2)  # Intersection: {3}
print(set1 - set2)  # Difference: {1, 2}
print(set1 ^ set2)  # Symmetric difference: {1, 2, 4, 5}
```

### Frozensets
```python
# Immutable sets
frozen = frozenset(["apple", "banana", "cherry"])

# Cannot be modified after creation
# frozen.add("orange")  # This would raise an AttributeError
```

## Boolean Type
```python
# Boolean values
is_valid = True
has_error = False

# Boolean operations
print(True and False)  # False
print(True or False)   # True
print(not True)        # False

# Boolean conversion
print(bool(0))       # False
print(bool(1))       # True
print(bool(""))      # False
print(bool("text"))  # True
print(bool([]))      # False
```

## None Type
```python
# None represents absence of a value
result = None

# Check for None using identity operator (is), not equality (==)
if result is None:
    print("No result yet")
```

## Collections Module
```python
from collections import namedtuple, Counter, defaultdict, deque

# Named tuple - a tuple with named fields
Person = namedtuple('Person', ['name', 'age', 'city'])
alice = Person('Alice', 30, 'New York')
print(alice.name)  # Alice
print(alice[0])    # Alice

# Counter - count occurrences of elements
words = ['apple', 'orange', 'apple', 'banana', 'apple', 'orange']
word_counts = Counter(words)
print(word_counts)  # Counter({'apple': 3, 'orange': 2, 'banana': 1})

# defaultdict - dictionary with default factory for missing keys
fruit_categories = defaultdict(list)
fruit_categories['sweet'].append('banana')
fruit_categories['citrus'].append('orange')
print(fruit_categories['sweet'])   # ['banana']
print(fruit_categories['bitter'])  # [] (creates an empty list rather than KeyError)

# deque - double-ended queue with fast appends and pops
queue = deque(['a', 'b', 'c'])
queue.append('d')           # Add to right
queue.appendleft('z')       # Add to left
print(queue)                # deque(['z', 'a', 'b', 'c', 'd'])
```

## Type Checking in Python

### Using `isinstance()` (recommended)
```python
# Check if object is an instance of a type or tuple of types
x = "Hello"
print(isinstance(x, str))             # True
print(isinstance(x, (str, int)))      # True (is instance of any in tuple)
print(isinstance(10, int))            # True
print(isinstance(3.14, float))        # True
```

### Using `type()`
```python
# Check exact type (not inheritance)
x = "Hello"
print(type(x) is str)                # True
print(type(x) == str)                # True
```

## Type Conversion (Casting)
```python
# Convert between types
x = 10
float_x = float(x)           # 10.0
string_x = str(x)            # "10"
bool_x = bool(x)             # True

y = "20"
int_y = int(y)               # 20

# Be careful with conversions that might fail
try:
    int_z = int("not a number")
except ValueError:
    print("Conversion failed")
```

## Custom Data Types with Classes
```python
class Point:
    def __init__(self, x, y):
        self.x = x
        self.y = y
    
    def distance_from_origin(self):
        return (self.x ** 2 + self.y ** 2) ** 0.5

# Create instances of your custom type
p1 = Point(3, 4)
print(p1.distance_from_origin())  # 5.0
```

## Type Annotations (Python 3.5+)
```python
def greet(name: str) -> str:
    return f"Hello, {name}"

def calculate_area(width: float, height: float) -> float:
    return width * height

# Advanced type annotations with typing module
from typing import List, Dict, Tuple, Optional

def process_items(items: List[str]) -> Dict[str, int]:
    result = {}
    for item in items:
        result[item] = len(item)
    return result

def get_user(user_id: int) -> Optional[dict]:
    # Returns user dict or None if not found
    pass
```

Understanding Python's data types is fundamental to effective Python programming. Each type has its own methods, behaviors, and use cases. The dynamic typing system allows for flexible code, but it's still important to understand what types you're working with to prevent errors and write efficient code."

"Based on the information I've gathered from these Stack Overflow questions and answers, I can provide a comprehensive summary of how to handle Maven dependency conflicts. Here's a summary of best practices and troubleshooting steps:

### Understanding Maven Dependency Conflicts

1. **Maven uses "nearest definition" principle**: The version used will be the closest one in your dependency tree. If dependencies A, B, and C are defined as A -> B -> C, and A -> D, then the path from A to D is shorter, so D's version will be used.

2. **Direct vs. Transitive dependencies**: 
   - Direct dependencies are explicitly declared in your pom.xml
   - Transitive dependencies are pulled in by your direct dependencies

### Best Practices for Resolving Maven Dependency Conflicts

1. **Use DependencyManagement section**:
   ```xml
   <dependencyManagement>
       <dependencies>
           <dependency>
               <groupId>com.example</groupId>
               <artifactId>library</artifactId>
               <version>1.2.3</version>
           </dependency>
       </dependencies>
   </dependencyManagement>
   ```
   This ensures you get the version you want, especially if one of your dependencies upgrades their version later.

2. **Run dependency analysis tools**:
   - `mvn dependency:tree` to visualize your dependency hierarchy
   - `mvn dependency:analyze` to find unused/undeclared dependencies

3. **Use exclusions for problematic transitive dependencies**:
   ```xml
   <dependency>
       <groupId>org.example</groupId>
       <artifactId>example-project</artifactId>
       <version>1.0</version>
       <exclusions>
           <exclusion>
               <groupId>commons-logging</groupId>
               <artifactId>commons-logging</artifactId>
           </exclusion>
       </exclusions>
   </dependency>
   ```

4. **Enforce dependency convergence** with Maven Enforcer Plugin:
   ```xml
   <plugin>
       <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
       <artifactId>maven-enforcer-plugin</artifactId>
       <version>3.0.0</version>
       <executions>
           <execution>
               <id>enforce-dependency-convergence</id>
               <goals>
                   <goal>enforce</goal>
               </goals>
               <configuration>
                   <rules>
                       <dependencyConvergence/>
                   </rules>
               </configuration>
           </execution>
       </executions>
   </plugin>
   ```

Based on these Stack Overflow resources, this approach will help systematically identify and resolve Maven dependency conflicts."

"Now that I've thoroughly explored the Stack Overflow question about Python list slicing and slice assignment, I'll create a comprehensive answer based on what I've learned.

# Python List Slicing: A Comprehensive Guide

## Basic List Slicing

Python's list slicing provides a powerful way to access portions of lists using the notation `a[start:stop:step]`. The basic syntax follows this pattern:
```python
my_list[start:end:step]
```

Where:
- `start`: Index to start slicing (inclusive)
- `end`: Index to end slicing (exclusive)
- `step`: Increment between indices (default is 1)

## Slice Assignment Rules

From the Stack Overflow post, I learned several important rules about slice assignment:

### Rule 1: Type Requirements
**Slicing returns a list, slice assignment requires a list (or other iterable)**
```python
# Example from the post
p = ['p', 'y', 't', 'h', 'o', 'n']
p[2:3]  # Returns ['t']
p[2:3] = ['T']  # Valid: assigning a list to a slice
p[2:3] = 't'    # Error: can only assign an iterable
```

### Rule 2: Symmetry of Slicing and Assignment
**Whatever portion of the list is returned by slice indexing is the same portion that is changed by slice assignment.**

```python
p = ['p', 'y', 't', 'h', 'o', 'n']
p[2:4]  # Returns ['t', 'h']
p[2:4] = ['T', 'H']  # Replaces those elements with new values
p  # Result: ['p', 'y', 'T', 'H', 'o', 'n']
```

### Rule 3: Flexible Length
**The assigned list doesn't have to have the same length as the slice it's replacing.**

```python
p = ['p', 'y', 't', 'h', 'o', 'n']
p[2:4] = ['s', 'p', 'a', 'm']  # Replace 2 elements with 4
p  # Result: ['p', 'y', 's', 'p', 'a', 'm', 'o', 'n']
```

## Empty Slice Assignment

One tricky part is understanding empty slice assignment:

```python
p = ['p', 'y', 't', 'h', 'o', 'n']
p[2:2] = ['x', 'y']  # Assigns list at position 2, no elements removed
p  # Result: ['p', 'y', 'x', 'y', 't', 'h', 'o', 'n']
```

The position for empty slice assignment is the logical extension of the positions for non-empty slice assignments.

## Heuristics for Understanding Slicing

1. **Zero-Based Thinking**: "Zero is the beginning, start at the beginning and take n items in a list"
   ```python
   p[0:3]  # Start at beginning and take 3 items
   ```

2. **Count and Chop**: "For any slice, replace the start by zero, apply the previous heuristic to get the end of the list, then count the first number back up to chop items off the beginning"
   ```python
   p[2:5]  # Start with p[0:5] then chop 2 elements off front
   ```

## Negative Slices

Slices with negative indices count from the end of the list:
```python
p = ['p', 'y', 't', 'h', 'o', 'n']
p[5:3:-1]  # Returns ['n', 'o']
```

In Python, it doesn't start slicing backwards automatically - you need to explicitly use a negative step.

## Error Protection

Python slicing is notably robust against errors:
```python
p[100:200]  # Returns [] instead of an error
p[int(2e9):int(1e9)]  # Also returns [] despite using massive indices
```

## Comparison Between Deletion Methods

When removing elements from a list:
```python
# Two ways to remove first element
l = l[1:]  # Creates new list, original unchanged
del l[0]   # Modifies list in place
```

The first way creates a new list (more memory but safer), while the second modifies the original list (more efficient but changes the original data).

## Practical Applications

Slice assignment is particularly useful for:
1. **Insertion**: Insert elements at a specific position
   ```python
   my_list[2:2] = ['new1', 'new2']  # Insert at position 2
   ```

2. **Replacement**: Replace a section of a list with new elements
   ```python
   my_list[1:3] = ['x', 'y', 'z']  # Replace elements at indices 1-2 with three new elements
   ```

3. **Deletion**: Remove elements by assigning an empty list
   ```python
   my_list[2:5] = []  # Remove elements at indices 2-4
   ```

4. **List manipulation**: Operation like in-place reversal or modification
   ```python
   # Reverse a portion of a list in-place
   my_list[2:6] = my_list[5:1:-1]
   ```

This updated answer provides detailed insights about Python list slicing with a special focus on slice assignment, complete with examples illustrating the key concepts and practical applications."

{"executive_summary": "The 2021 Travel Weekly Travel Industry Survey reflects the reality most travel advisors have lived through these past 20 months: Personal income in free fall, cancellations and rebookings skyrocketing. Staff on furlough, business plans rejiggered, expenses cut.

For the most part, the survey confirms, in raw data, the subjective experiences that travel advisors have been sharing with Travel Weekly reporters and readers for more than a year and a half of crisis.

The delta variant taught us to be cautious about making predictions, but there are directional clues in the data. The timeline on the chart "A pandemic return to the Great Recession sales decline" is simultaneously depressing and hopeful: While it gives graphic expression to the plunge in agency sales, it also shows that, historically, when recovery takes hold (as it did in the third year after the Great Recession began), business revenue normalizes and, barring another crisis, stays normalized.

That's not to say that business or life will be the same as it was before the pandemic. Crisis or not, no two years are ever the same, and we wouldn't want them to be. Exciting new products come on the market. Tech innovations offer improvements to how we do business and the travel experience. As clients move through life's passages, what they want out of a vacation changes.

There is one chart in particular that I believe offers some clues about a significant shift in travel sales that may have real staying power: the one on this page.

This chart illustrates the recent dramatic change in sales of domestic versus international travel. For 17 years, there had been a slow, steady decline in domestic bookings matched by a slow, steady increase in international sales. The sudden reversal of this very consistent trend, one that remained unchanged even during the recession, is one of the most dramatic reversals in the study.

On one hand, there's an obvious explanation: With the exception of travel to Mexico, international travel ranged from exasperating to impossible. Varying, complex, confusing and inconsistent border entry requirements — if borders weren't closed completely — made domestic travel infinitely more attractive in 2020 and thus far through 2021.

Although historical data shows many customary travel patterns return relatively soon after a crisis, I'm not sure the return to international travel dominance will be swift. Many people who felt a vacation wasn't a vacation unless it put a stamp into their passport discovered the appeal of modern travel within the U.S.

And, specifically, consumers discovered the pleasure of visiting nonurban destinations within the U.S. While hotels remained shuttered in major cities, tertiary cities and resorts within 100 miles of highly populated areas were enjoying record average daily rates. Reinvesting their windfalls — and there is indeed evidence that these resorts and hotels are working to capitalize and expand upon their recent popularity, particularly in outdoor and adventure activities — will only make nonurban resorts and smaller cities all the more attractive.

We've also seen tour operators, river cruise lines and rail companies expand their U.S. offerings during the pandemic. If these remain in place — and indications are they've been well-received — it will expand domestic product breadth and inventory.

As you read through the charts in this year's Travel Industry Survey, you may notice other changes you believe indicate secular, rather than temporary, change. I'd be interested in hearing your thoughts. As always, you can email me at aweissmann@travelweekly.com.

Arnie Weissmann
Executive Vice President and Editor in Chief, Travel Weekly"}

Anthropic_Output:
"Great! I now have all the information I need to create a wiki-style answer about how cryptocurrencies work. Based on the content from Answers.com, I'll prepare a comprehensive response that incorporates technical details along with easy-to-understand examples.

# How Do Cryptocurrencies Work?

## Introduction
Cryptocurrencies are digital or virtual currencies that use cryptography for security and operate on a technology called blockchain. Unlike traditional currencies issued by governments, cryptocurrencies function through a decentralized network of computers.

## Blockchain Technology
**Definition**: A blockchain is a distributed ledger that records all transactions across a network of computers. Each block in the chain contains a list of transactions, and once a block is filled, it is added to the chain in a linear and chronological order.

**Decentralization**: Unlike traditional currencies controlled by central banks, cryptocurrencies are decentralized and managed by a network of nodes (computers). This means no single entity has complete control over the currency.

**Example**: Think of a blockchain as a public spreadsheet that anyone can view but no single person can modify without consensus. When you make a transaction, it's like adding a new row to this spreadsheet that everyone can verify.

## Cryptography
**Security**: Cryptocurrencies use cryptographic techniques to secure transactions, control the creation of new units, and verify the transfer of assets. This ensures that transactions are secure and that the identity of users can remain anonymous.

**Public and Private Keys**: Each user has a pair of keys:
- **Public Key**: Similar to an account number, it can be shared with others to receive funds.
- **Private Key**: Like a password, it must be kept secret and is used to sign transactions and access the cryptocurrency.

**Example**: Imagine your public key as your email address (which you can share with anyone) and your private key as the password to your email (which you keep secret). Anyone can send you cryptocurrency using your public key, but only you can access and transfer it using your private key.

## Transactions
When a user wants to send cryptocurrency to another user, they create a transaction that includes the amount, the recipient's public key, and their own private key for verification. This transaction is then broadcast to the network, where it is verified by nodes.

**Example**: If Alice wants to send 1 Bitcoin to Bob, she creates a transaction specifying the amount and Bob's public address. She signs this transaction with her private key to prove she owns the Bitcoin being sent. The network then verifies and records this transaction.

## Mining and Consensus Mechanisms
**Mining**: In many cryptocurrencies (like Bitcoin), transactions are verified through a process called mining, where powerful computers compete to solve complex mathematical problems. The first to solve the problem gets to add the block of transactions to the blockchain and is rewarded with cryptocurrency.

**Consensus Mechanisms**: Other cryptocurrencies might use different methods to achieve consensus on the network, like Proof of Stake (PoS) or Delegated Proof of Stake (DPoS), which have different rules for validating transactions.

**Example**: Think of mining as a competition where participants solve complex puzzles. The first to solve the puzzle gets to add a new page to the ledger (blockchain) and receives newly created cryptocurrency as a reward.

## Supply Control
Most cryptocurrencies have a predetermined supply limit. For instance, Bitcoin has a maximum supply of 21 million coins, which creates scarcity and can influence value. New coins are generally introduced into circulation through mining or staking, depending on the consensus mechanism.

**Example**: Unlike traditional currencies that can be printed at will by governments, Bitcoin is designed to have a limited supply – similar to precious metals like gold, which cannot be created but only discovered.

## Wallets
To store and manage cryptocurrency, users need digital wallets. These can be:
- **Hot Wallets**: Connected to the internet, allowing for quick access but are more susceptible to hacks.
- **Cold Wallets**: Offline storage, such as hardware wallets, providing more security but less convenience for transactions.

**Example**: A hot wallet is like keeping cash in your physical wallet – convenient for everyday use but risky to store large amounts. A cold wallet is like a safety deposit box – more secure but less convenient to access regularly.

## Exchanges
Cryptocurrencies can be bought, sold, or traded on cryptocurrency exchanges. These platforms allow users to exchange fiat money (like USD or EUR) for cryptocurrencies and vice versa.

**Example**: Cryptocurrency exchanges function similar to stock exchanges, where you can convert traditional money into digital assets and trade different cryptocurrencies.

## Regulation and Adoption
The regulatory environment for cryptocurrencies varies by country, affecting how they can be used and traded. Adoption is growing, with many businesses beginning to accept cryptocurrencies as a form of payment, while others are exploring the underlying blockchain technology for various applications beyond currency.

## Conclusion
Cryptocurrencies represent a new paradigm in finance, leveraging cryptographic security, decentralized networks, and innovative consensus mechanisms. They enable peer-to-peer transactions without intermediaries, creating both opportunities and challenges in the financial landscape."

{"answer_text": "Climate change significantly impacts global agriculture in various ways. Here’s a detailed breakdown of the main effects:

1. Temperature Changes
- Crop Yields: Increased temperatures can reduce crop yields for temperature-sensitive crops like wheat, rice, and maize. Many crops have optimal temperature ranges, and exceeding these can lead to stress and reduced productivity.
- Growing Seasons: Warmer temperatures may extend growing seasons in some regions, allowing for additional harvests. However, in hotter climates, this could also lead to heat stress and lower yields.

2. Precipitation Patterns
- Altered Rainfall: Changes in precipitation patterns can result in droughts or flooding. Regions that rely on consistent rainfall may face severe water shortages, affecting irrigation and crop growth.
- Soil Moisture: Increased rainfall intensity can lead to soil erosion and reduced soil moisture retention, impacting the ability of crops to thrive.

3. Extreme Weather Events
- Storms and Flooding: More frequent and severe storms can destroy crops and delay planting or harvesting. Flooding can lead to soil degradation and loss of nutrients.
- Droughts: Prolonged droughts can lead to crop failures and increased irrigation demands, putting further stress on water resources.

4. Pests and Diseases
- Increased Pest Pressure: Warmer temperatures can expand the range and lifecycle of agricultural pests and diseases, leading to increased infestations and potential crop losses.
- New Pathogens: Climate change can introduce new diseases to crops that were previously unaffected, complicating pest management and increasing reliance on pesticides.

5. Soil Health
- Degradation: Changes in weather patterns can lead to soil erosion, loss of organic matter, and degradation of soil health, which are crucial for sustainable agriculture.
- Nutrient Cycling: Altered temperature and moisture conditions can impact nutrient cycling in soils, affecting the availability of essential nutrients for plant growth.

6. Water Resources
- Irrigation Stress: With changing precipitation patterns, many regions may face a decrease in available freshwater for irrigation, leading to increased competition for water resources.
- Groundwater Depletion: Increased irrigation demands can lead to over-extraction of groundwater, which is often unsustainable.

7. Economic Impacts
- Market Fluctuations: Changes in agricultural productivity can lead to fluctuations in food prices, impacting food security and economic stability in vulnerable regions.
- Adaptation Costs: Farmers may face increased costs for adapting to climate change, including investing in new technologies and practices to maintain yields.

8. Regional Variability
- Differential Impacts: Some regions may benefit from climate change (e.g., northern latitudes might see longer growing seasons), while others, particularly in tropical and subtropical areas, may suffer greatly.

9. Adaptation Strategies
- Crop Diversification: Farmers may shift to more resilient crop varieties or diversify crops to mitigate risks.
- Sustainable Practices: Implementing sustainable agricultural practices such as conservation tillage, agroforestry, and integrated pest management can help build resilience against climate impacts.

Conclusion

Overall, climate change poses significant challenges to global agriculture, affecting food security, farmer livelihoods, and ecosystem health. Mitigation and adaptation strategies are essential to cope with these changes and ensure sustainable agricultural systems in the future.", "source_url": "https://www.answers.com/search?q=climate+change+affecting+global+agriculture"}

{"seasonal_planting_tips": "As winter comes to an end and the last frost has passed, it's time to assess your garden and plan for a spring refresh. Here are the key seasonal planting tips from the article:

1. Wild Gardens: Embrace a more informal, natural look by densely planting native and exotic species in patterns that mimic nature. Opt for wildflowers, native grasses, and plants that require little water. Consider adding water features like ponds for a Mother Nature-inspired touch.

2. Edible Gardens: Incorporate fruit trees and vegetable patches, even in small spaces. You don't need to be a farmer—just carve out a spot for herbs, veggies, and fruit trees. Growing your own food is a continuing trend, and harvesting fresh ingredients from your garden is rewarding.

3. Bold Color & Texture: While classic green-and-white gardens remain popular, experiment with texture using variegated foliage, different leaf shapes, and contrasting textures. For color, go bold with rich, saturated hues like deep blues, hot pinks, and vivid purples. Alternatively, try a monochromatic palette for a serene, modern vibe.

4. Water-Smart Landscaping: With increasing droughts and heat, choose drought-tolerant plants such as succulents and natives. Use mulching techniques to retain moisture and design gardens that thrive with minimal watering. Select the right plant for the right place, and use smart irrigation.

5. Pollinator Gardens: Plant nectar- and pollen-rich flowers to attract bees, butterflies, birds, and ladybugs. Use native plants like milkweeds, mountain mints, and asters. Leave leaves as natural mulch to provide habitat for overwintering insects, and consider bee hotels and water pans to support pollinators.

6. Nostalgia Gardens: Recreate the gardens of your childhood with sentimental flowers like lilacs and roses, wildflowers, and classic elements such as stepping stones and benches. This trend encourages reconnecting with nature and appreciating simple pleasures.

General Advice: Always consider your USDA hardiness zone, the amount of sun your garden receives, and your willingness to maintain the space. Staying updated on design and edging ideas will help keep your garden healthy and beautiful throughout the season."}
